fic failure mode]' and clarify what 'repair' operationally means."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 50, "claim_text": "switching resistance in this population is proposed to operate differently from inertia", "why_matters": "The claim that Enacted Fidelity 'breaks under betrayal rather than inconvenience' asserts a causal relationship without mechanism: how does relational interpretation of betrayal causally prevent switching, and through what cognitive/behavioral path?", "correction": "Add mechanism: specify how the relational framing causally prevents switching (e.g., 'relational framing increases psychological cost of switching by X process') and cite or provide evidence for the pathway."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 54, "claim_text": "Enacted Fidelity...is governed by relational logic: it breaks under betrayal rather than inconvenience", "why_matters": "Asserts that betrayal interpretation causes switching resistance to operate differently without explaining the causal mechanism linking relational framing to differential switching behavior.", "correction": "Explain: 'Relational framing causes resistance to break under betrayal because [mechanism], whereas transactional framing causes resistance to break under convenience because [mechanism].'"}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 71, "claim_text": "The Contract Window makes the model's reasoning state inspectable without requiring users to evaluate the full reasoning chain.", "why_matters": "The claim that the Contract Window 'makes' reasoning inspectable asserts a causal capability without explaining the mechanism of how inspection occurs or what technical processes enable it.", "correction": "Add a mechanism: explain what technical affordances or design features enable inspection, or use hedged language like 'aims to make' or 'is designed to support' inspection."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 76, "claim_text": "This work extends that literature by identifying the interpretive framework failure \u2014 not just the discriminatory output \u2014 as the safety-critical inte", "why_matters": "Claims that identifying interpretive framework failures 'as' an intervention site will improve safety, without stating the mechanism by which this identification leads to better outcomes.", "correction": "Explain how identifying the framework failure as an intervention point causally leads to safer systems, or soften to 'proposes that interpretive framework failures represent a promising intervention site.'"}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 83, "claim_text": "Insight Atrophy... targeted degradation of *investigative* capacity within a single interaction, when a model answers in a way that forecloses the inv", "why_matters": "The claim that a model answer 'forecloses' investigation asserts a causal effect on user investigative capacity without a stated mechanism of how single answers degrade future investigative capacity.", "correction": "Add mechanism: explain how a single fluent answer causally produces investigative capacity loss, or cite evidence (e.g., pilot study, user study) showing this effect."}, {"code": "OC-5", "line_number": 87, "claim_text": "A search of ACM Digital Library, Semantic Scholar, and Google Scholar... returned no published work matching this description", "why_matters": "An absolute zero-result claim ('no published work') is stated without specifying the exact search corpus size, how many results were screened, or how edge cases (preprints, grey literature, non-English works) were handled.", "correction": "State the number of results returned by each search, how many were screened for inclusion, and what criteria determined eligibility."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 82, "claim_text": "The Contract Window enforces this by making T explicit, inspectable, and blocking outputs for which T is incomplete.", "why_matters": "Claims a causal enforcement mechanism ('enforces') without explaining HOW the Contract Window technically blocks outputs or what system components execute this blocking.", "correction": "Add mechanism: Specify the technical architecture that detects incomplete traces T and the computational process by which outputs are prevented from being produced."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 83, "claim_text": "C feeds back into S when invariants remain unsatisfied \u2014 a governed loop, not a one-pass pipeline.", "why_matters": "Claims a feedback mechanism 'governs' the loop but provides no explanation of HOW the system detects unsatisfied invariants or routes information back to S.", "correction": "Explain the control mechanism: What signal triggers feedback? How does the system detect invariant violation? What state representation enables re-entry to S?"}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 84, "claim_text": "A model that satisfies I1\u2013I7 without accounting for I8 is doing arithmetic without understanding the number system.", "why_matters": "Makes a causal claim that omitting narrative (I8) 'causes' a loss of understanding, but provides no mechanism showing HOW narrative enables or prevents model understanding.", "correction": "Specify the epistemic mechanism: How does narrative layer presence/absence affect model behavior, inference, or validity? Provide a concrete example of failure without I8."}, {"code": "OC-5", "line_number": 434, "claim_text": "all tests passing as of pre-submission archive", "why_matters": "Absolute rate claim (62/62 green) without stating what the test corpus covers, what edge cases were included, or what failure modes the tests actually verify.", "correction": "State explicitly: (1) what each test validates (e.g., invariant enforcement, repair obligation triggering, channel disagreement detection); (2) whether tests cover adversarial inputs, boundary conditions, or only happy-path scenarios; (3) whether 62 tests represent unit, integration, or system-level coverage."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 372, "claim_text": "The Halt Authority prevents the model from proceeding to output while any invariant is unsatisfied", "why_matters": "Claims a system 'prevents' an outcome without stating the mechanism: how does Halt Authority technically block output? What happens when it triggers? How are conflicts between channels resolved if they disagree on invariant satisfaction?", "correction": "Add: (1) the technical mechanism (e.g., exception handling, API gate, token masking); (2) what the model observes when halted; (3) how the repair obligation is communicated and executed."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 389, "claim_text": "Bicameral Review catches both failure modes independently, because each is invisible to the other's evaluation criteria", "why_matters": "Claims the system 'catches' failure modes via structural invisibility without explaining the mechanism: how does invisibility prevent one channel from reinforcing the other's error? What happens if both channels fail in the same direction?", "correction": "Clarify: (1) what architectural properties enforce independence (e.g., separate prompts, isolated state, different LLM instances); (2) how cascading failure is prevented; (3) empirical evidence that the channels disagree on real examples."}, {"code": "OC-6", "line_number": 434, "claim_text": "The implementation includes: `contract_window.py` ... All components are tested (62/62 green; see CI artifact)", "why_matters": "The text describes six runtime invariants (I1\u2013I6) in Halt Authority but earlier describes Eight Wonders as the core mechanism. The relationship between I1\u2013I6 and the Eight Wonders is never clarified; it is unclear if they are the same, overlapping, or distinct systems.", "correction": "Explicitly state: (1) are I1\u2013I6 the operationalization of the Eight Wonders, or are they separate? (2) if operationalization, provide the mapping; (3) if separate, explain why both are necessary and how they interact."}, {"code": "OC-5", "line_number": 161, "claim_text": "Sessions running to hundreds of thousands of tokens showed no observed degradation in constitutional compliance.", "why_matters": "The claim of no degradation across massive token counts requires stating: what metric quantifies 'constitutional compliance', how many sessions were measured, what constitutes a degradation threshold, and how was compliance sampled or evaluated across the token range.", "correction": "Add a specific compliance metric (e.g., 'V&T invariant satisfaction rate'), state the corpus size (number of sessions, token ranges tested), define the degradation threshold, and cite the audit methodology or artifact demonstrating the measurement."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 182, "claim_text": "V&T statement as cognitive anchor... stabilizing mechanism in long sessions.", "why_matters": "The claim that V&T 'acts as' or 'stabilizes' requires a causal mechanism explaining HOW the statement prevents drift or improves coherence, not merely that models reported using it or that compliance was observed.", "correction": "Explain the mechanism: Does V&T reduce token-level deviation from a baseline? Does it gate output before generation? Add quantitative evidence (e.g., compliance scores with/without V&T, or token-level divergence metrics) to support the stabilization claim."}, {"code": "OC-6", "line_number": 166, "claim_text": "Kimi independently embedded 'V&T STATEMENT REQUIRED' directive into every cognitive mode level... treating V&T as a constitutional invariant... withou", "why_matters": "The claim asserts Kimi acted 'without instruction' yet the user submitted a request to 'refactor the text into a five-level cognitive mode-based prompt stack'\u2014this constitutes instruction to structure output, potentially biasing the model toward adding structure including V&T-like tagging.", "correction": "Clarify whether the user prompt included any language requesting epistemic tagging, structural invariants, or truth-status marking. If not, state that explicitly. If yes, revise the claim to 'without explicit V&T instruction' and explain why V&T adoption still constitutes generalization beyond the refactoring task."}, {"code": "OC-5", "line_number": 182, "claim_text": "Cross-architecture convergence on the same structural solution \u2014 without those sessions having access to each other \u2014 is interpreted as evidence that ", "why_matters": "The claim requires stating: how many models were tested, what exact prompts elicited the Contract Window concept, were the responses verbatim identical or similar in intent, and how were 'independence' and 'convergence' operationalized and measured across the corpus.", "correction": "Create a comparison table in supplementary material listing: model name, session date, exact user prompt, model response excerpt, and structural similarity score. State the sample size and whether convergence was assessed via manual coding, embedding similarity, or another metric."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 421, "claim_text": "Gemini...created a new file, preserved the CI pipeline, and explained the reasoning...treating the deviation as something that needed to be on the rec", "why_matters": "The claim that Gemini's file creation demonstrates 'constitutional judgment' lacks a stated mechanism for how rule-following behavior (or heuristic deviation) produces legal/governance reasoning.", "correction": "State explicitly: Does 'constitutional judgment' mean (a) adherence to a constraint, (b) explicit reasoning about trade-offs, or (c) autonomous value alignment? Specify what model behavior would distinguish 'constitutional judgment' from sophisticated rule-following."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 432, "claim_text": "Constitutional compliance at the model level may be less important than constitutional awareness at the human relay level", "why_matters": "This causal claim about what 'matters' for compliance lacks a mechanism: no definition of how 'awareness' produces 'compliance' or how to measure compliance improvement.", "correction": "Define operationally: What observable outputs or behavioral changes result from 'constitutional awareness'? How would you detect compliance degradation if the human relay layer became unreliable?"}, {"code": "OC-6", "line_number": 429, "claim_text": "The researcher made explicit curation decisions in each transfer: retaining or stripping the V&T statement depending on whether it would advance or di", "why_matters": "Section 9, Limitation 1 states observations are 'not controlled experiments' with 'no blinding'; yet this observation claims the researcher made deliberate curation choices without disclosing whether the decision criterion (advance/distract) was pre-specified or post-hoc assigned.", "correction": "Clarify: Were the curation rules defined before or after observing model responses? If post-hoc, label this as hypothesis-generating, not as evidence of a 'defined governance role.'"}, {"code": "OC-5", "line_number": 463, "claim_text": "The Eight Wonders of Black Shopping are not a diversity addendum...they are a demonstration that culturally situated heuristics provide higher signal ", "why_matters": "The claim asserts a comparative performance statement ('higher signal density') without stating: (a) what corpus was used to measure baseline performance, (b) how many comparisons were run, or (c) what 'signal density' metric was applied.", "correction": "Provide explicit performance metrics: Report baseline accuracy/signal on undifferentiated data, accuracy on Eight Wonders-informed models, sample size, and confidence intervals or statistical significance tests."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 468, "claim_text": "Failing to use [culturally situated heuristics] produces not just inaccurate models but unsafe ones", "why_matters": "The claim asserts that omission of the heuristics causes unsafety without stating a mechanism linking heuristic absence to specific unsafe outcomes.", "correction": "Specify the causal chain: How does model inaccuracy on [specific behavior] lead to [specific harm]? Link to the pricing/credit/surveillance examples cited, with hypothesized failure modes."}, {"code": "OC-6", "line_number": 473, "claim_text": "The TLC Guardian Kernel is a working prototype, not production-tested under load or against adversarial inputs", "why_matters": "Section 8, Observation 4 describes the Kernel as functionally enforcing 'constitutional judgment' and executing deviation management; Section 9.5 then downgrades it to 'prototype' status\u2014contradicting the authority claims made in Observation 4.", "correction": "Clarify developmental status: Is the Kernel already enforcing governance decisions (as Observation 4 implies) or still exploratory? If the former, state what load/adversarial testing has occurred; if the latter, reframe Observation 4 as proof-of-concept only."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 195, "claim_text": "Cognitively safe AI must: train on Narrative-Events, not just tokens; govern through Invariants, not just filters; preserve Discovery", "why_matters": "Causal claims that these training/governance approaches produce cognitive safety lack any stated mechanism explaining HOW they achieve this outcome.", "correction": "Add a mechanism section explaining: (1) why narrative events specifically reduce unsafe outputs, (2) how invariants prevent failure modes that filters miss, (3) what discovery preservation accomplishes for safety."}, {"code": "OC-3", "line_number": 196, "claim_text": "require Feedback at every state change... It is time to make them more honest.", "why_matters": "Claims that mandatory feedback 'makes models more honest' is a causal assertion without explaining the mechanism linking state-change feedback to honesty improvements.", "correction": "Specify the causal pathway: e.g., 'Feedback at every state change enables [mechanism], which reduces [dishonesty failure mode], because [why this works better than status quo].'"}], "status": "NEEDS_AUTHOR_REVIEW"}
